"Car Bee" prevents collisions
This time Nissan was inspired by the development of accident-protection technologies in nature, specifically in bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the pattern of flying bees to prevent collisions.
Such is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in the prevention of precipitation technologies.
Engineers of the Centre for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. robot developed in cooperation with the Centre for Progress in Scientific and Technological Research the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doie, Director-General of Public Relations for Technology, Research and Brand Development, BR23C is presented as an extension of the four areas of the safety shield of Nissan.
The robot has the task of strengthening the ability to prevent precipitation in vehicles of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the safety shield of Nissan.
But the most important are the folded bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions an angle greater than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
When the engineers created this visual function, they suggested what they called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It records obstacles that are up to a distance of two meters in a 180-degree radius before BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends the signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a warning against the collision.
"When the obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics the bee movements and immediately changes the direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobile Laboratory and the main engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards and diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction by which it is possible to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities like bees.
In addition to the acceleration and slowdown, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent a collision.
"The equipment only needs to process the information every few seconds and to be maintained according to this data.
It does not require storage of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we don't talk about a gig or a mega."
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of precipitation, a technology where Nissan predicts the use of serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the goal and avoid obstacles on the road.
