The fox in the hen house
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with the applicant on the basis of data on drug purchases.
Data protection experts are concerned that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of data on prescription of medicines in any case, subject to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken fox," quotes Washington Post Richard Dick, the author of a program designed to monitor prescriptions.
The insurance company shall make the insurance and the amounts paid in the event of insurance events dependent on the health of the persons concerned and, if the risk is assessed too large, shall not close the insurance with it.
They used to send the concerned to medical examination and the contract was concluded only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the pharmacies identification number, the customer can easily find out what drugs he bought in the last year and a half, from which the program is self-inflicted, what disease he's suffering from and what his condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys a large number of cholesterol-lowering medicines, this refers to the fact that he has virtually uncontrollably high levels of blood fats, which immediately puts him in a higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the programme in circulation, some of them also determine the risk factor, so that there is hardly any work left to the insurance company in addition to the paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
The disadvantages are that many medicines can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds are used against migraines or hot flushes, but are also effective against depression.
These represent, from the point of view of commercial insurance companies, a significant risk-increasing factor, while not the first-named difficulties.
In order to request and process the data, special companies were created which, before they could obtain the necessary information from the pharmacies, would ask the patient for permission.
They are already forcing the authorities to do so, even though they have not punished them for their negligence so far.
Some companies have already processed the results of laboratory tests that combine data on the medicines used, so that they can provide an even more accurate picture of the patient’s health condition.
More and more companies have access to the data, while checking their use will become more and more complex.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give the authorities the power to control also companies specialising in the provision of data, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his programme so that the transfer of data is linked to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that the permission in question can hardly be denied, or the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with it.
So the hens are a little bit dependent on the fox's goodwill.
